		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Photodiode</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:272px;"><a href="/wiki/File:CD-ROM_Photodetector.jpg" class="image" title="Photodetector from a CD-ROM Drive. Visible are 3 photodiodes."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/d/d1/CD-ROM_Photodetector.jpg/270px-CD-ROM_Photodetector.jpg" width="270" height="203" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:CD-ROM_Photodetector.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Photodetector from a CD-ROM Drive. Visible are 3 photodiodes.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:77px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Photodiode.jpg" class="image" title="A photodiode"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/Photodiode.jpg/75px-Photodiode.jpg" width="75" height="379" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Photodiode.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
A photodiode</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>A <b>photodiode</b> is a type of <a href="/wiki/Photodetector" title="Photodetector">photodetector</a> capable of converting <a href="/wiki/Light" title="Light">light</a> into either <a href="/wiki/Electric_current" title="Electric current">current</a> or <a href="/wiki/Voltage" title="Voltage">voltage</a>, depending upon the mode of operation.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p>Photodiodes are similar to regular <a href="/wiki/Semiconductor" title="Semiconductor">semiconductor</a> <a href="/wiki/Diode" title="Diode">diodes</a> except that they may be either exposed (to detect <a href="/wiki/Vacuum_UV" title="Vacuum UV" class="mw-redirect">vacuum UV</a> or <a href="/wiki/X-rays" title="X-rays" class="mw-redirect">X-rays</a>) or packaged with a window or <a href="/wiki/Optical_fiber" title="Optical fiber">optical fibre</a> connection to allow light to reach the sensitive part of the device. Many diodes designed for use specifically as a photodiode will also use a <a href="/wiki/PIN_diode" title="PIN diode">PIN junction</a> rather than the typical <a href="/wiki/PN_junction" title="PN junction" class="mw-redirect">PN junction</a>.</p>
